ntral Facility and Academic Service Building&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		&lt;strong&gt;Faculty of Environmental Management&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Faculty of Pharmaceutical Sciences&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Faculty of Natural resources&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Faculty of Engineering&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Faculty of Agro-Industry&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Faculty of Liberal Arts&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Faculty of Management Sciences&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Computer Center&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Faculty of Law&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Information Technology Building&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Sports Complex/ Gymnasium&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Student Union/ Food Center&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Student Dormitories&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Reservoir&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Srisarp Gate (Punnakan Road Gate)&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Prince of Songkla University International Convention Center&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Mor-Or Withayanusorn School&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Faculty and staff Residential area&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ol&gt;\r\n', 'nopic.png', '2010-06-28'),
(9, 'Thai Medicine', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;images/medicine.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; height: 200px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Many questions are often asked about Thai medicine: How is it different from modern medicine? What are its strengths? How is it learned and taught?&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;At the outset, it is necessary to define Thai medicine. According to Practice of the Art of Healing Act, Thai medicine is examination, diagnosis, cure or prevention of disease by means of Thai traditional medicine. The process of learning and teaching Thai medicine includes both theory and practice sessions. Theory sessions deal with diagnosis based on Thai traditional medicine with reference to scriptures, such as the Takkasila Scripture, the Chantasat Scripture and the Pathomjinda Scripture. Further, the causes of a disease, its symptoms and its pathology are compared as between Thai traditional medicine and modern medicine. Finally, treatment, the formulation of Thai medicinal recipes, the prescribing of Thai medicine and referral are discussed in these sessions. Practice sessions emphasize practical considerations. Students undertake field work by seeing patients in the community. They also learn from Thai traditional doctors working in villages and study and observe how doctors practicing modern medicine give diagnoses in hospitals. They also observe children&amp;rsquo;s behavior and development at nurseries. Last but not least, they undertake internships at different hospitals all over the country.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; Graduates are expected to be able to apply what they have learned of Thai traditional medicine to the fullest extent and treat patients effectively based on the principles and objectives of Thai traditional medicine.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Strength&lt;/strong&gt; Thai traditional medicine is a source of national pride which has been used to treat patients for centuries. Even though these days, many Thai people prefer modern medicine, Thai traditional medicine is still useful and appropriate for the social and economic conditions existing in Thailand.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;How is it different from modern medicine?&lt;/strong&gt; The explanatory model is different. Modern medicine explains diseases as far as possible based on science. Modern medicine has its origins in germ theory which sought to explain many abnormalities in the body as resulting from micro-organisms. When treating patients, doctors in modern medicine focus on abnormality in the body, such as abnormal or infected organs and cells or the presence of abnormal chemicals, to diagnose what illness patients have or what is not normal in the body. Afterwards, they prescribe medicine or repair organs by, for example, stitching a wound, incising a cyst, prescribing medication to kill germs or stop the production of chemicals in the body and to repair abnormal cells. They sometimes forget that some medicines cause excruciating pain. At times physical pain or illness is relieved or treated, but what remains is mental pain and distress.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; Students of Thai traditional medicine have to study and gain basic knowledge about the cause of illness, pathophysiology and the approach to treatment adopted by modern medicine. Thai traditional medicine also takes into account the relationship between elements of the body, season, the patient&amp;rsquo;s age and behavior, and the time and place, viewing them as integrally interconnected. Thai traditional medicine, therefore, diagnoses and treats disorders based on an approach which places emphasis on the patient and their circumstances, for example, their families, communities and environment. The services given focus on individual patients combined with the physical, biological, psychological and social environment.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', 'nopic.png', '2010-06-28'),
(10, 'Thai Drugs', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;images/dung.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; height: 200px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;The use of Thai drugs is one area of Thai traditional medicine. Students learn about the benefits and forms of herbal medicine, and methods of preparing quality drugs. Students begin by studying Pharmaceutical and Folk Botany to understand the differences between families of plants. To be able to apply this knowledge to treat patients, they also take related courses in pharmacy. The subject areas are as follows:&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;strong&gt;1.&lt;span class=&quot;Apple-tab-span&quot; style=&quot;white-space:pre&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;Materia Medica:&lt;/strong&gt; Students study plants, animals and elements that can be used in the treatment of disorders.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;2.&lt;span class=&quot;Apple-tab-span&quot; style=&quot;white-space:pre&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;Medicinal Characteristics:&lt;/strong&gt; Students study modern and Thai traditional pharmacy. They gain knowledge of the major substances found in each herb and also acquire laboratory skills.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;strong&gt;3.&lt;span class=&quot;Apple-tab-span&quot; style=&quot;white-space:pre&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;Combining Materia Medica:&lt;/strong&gt; Students study how to combine herbal medicines to acquire skills in using herbal medicine to treat patients.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;strong&gt;4.&lt;span class=&quot;Apple-tab-span&quot; style=&quot;white-space:pre&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;Traditional Pharmaceutics:&lt;/strong&gt; Students study how to select quality material in order to prepare and produce different herbal medicines according to Thai traditional medicine methods.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Further, the course entitled Medicinal Plants for High Incidence Diseases discusses the use of herbs in basic health services, traditional household remedies, traditional drugs in the national list of essential medicines and the laws relating to the production and distribution of traditional medicines. In order to gain an in-depth knowledge of Thai drugs, students have to gain practical experience of their use. The Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine employs different strategies to promote the development of this body of knowledge, for example, students may undertake forest trekking with Thai traditional doctors, or engage in the production of herbal medicine under the &amp;ldquo;Thai Traditional Medicine for the Community&amp;rdquo; program. Additionally, they can undertake Thai pharmacy internships at community hospitals in different regions of Thailand and the Faculty also promotes students&amp;rsquo; research projects relating to the development of the knowledge and use of herbs.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;', 'nopic.png', '2010-06-28'),
(11, 'Thai Massage & Thai Midwifery', '&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;images/massage.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; height: 200px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n&lt;h3&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Thai Massage&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; The Traditional Thai Medicine curriculum offers courses in Thai massage as follows:&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;1.&lt;span class=&quot;Apple-tab-span&quot; style=&quot;white-space:pre&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;Thai Massage Courses: &lt;/strong&gt;Students study the history and evolution of Thai massage. There are 2 types of Thai message: Chaloey Sak (independent massage) and Ratchasamnak (court massage). Students study the body&amp;rsquo;s ten major lines (Sen Pratan Sip), the disorders caused by abnormalities in the body&amp;rsquo;s ten major lines and their treatment and rehabilitation by Thai massage. Students should also be able to evaluate patients&amp;rsquo; symptoms so that they can give them a referral to doctors in modern medicine in a timely manner.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;2.&lt;span class=&quot;Apple-tab-span&quot; style=&quot;white-space:pre&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;Thai Massage: &lt;/strong&gt;Students study massage therapy for partial paralysis, paralysis, migraine, sprained ankle, neck stiffness, Lom Plai Pattakat Sanyan 1, 3 Lang, Lom Plai Pattakat Sanyan 4, 5 Lang and Jap Pong Haeng/Nam Kao, by means of Ratchasamnak massage (court massage). The approach taken is a combination of theories from Thai traditional medicine and modern medicine. Students practice giving Thai massage to promote health according to the principles of Thai traditional medicine and the wisdom of Thai traditional doctors.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Apart from theory and practice sessions, students have to undertake internships at community hospitals nationwide in order to gain first-hand experience, acquire professional skills and apply the theory of examination and treatment in real situations.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; The key to the study of Thai massage is the weight of the hands or fingers. Students have to practice by crossing their legs, forming their fingers into a bowl shape and lifting themselves up. They learn and master this so that they can acquire quality hand or finger weight which will lead to quality treatment.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n\r\n\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;images/midwi.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; height: 200px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n&lt;h3&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Thai midwifery &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;\r\n&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;Thai midwifery refers to the examination, care, counseling and the promotion of health in pregnant women. It also includes the prevention of abnormality during pregnancy or delivery and the rendering of assistance in childbirth by means of Thai traditional medicine&lt;/strong&gt; (according to the Practice of the Art of Healing Unit). In the Thai traditional medicine curriculum, students study both the theory of Thai midwifery and modern midwifery, in the hope that students will be able to work effectively with professionals from other fields. The courses students take are as follows:&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;1.&lt;span class=&quot;Apple-tab-span&quot; style=&quot;white-space:pre&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;Thai Midwifery&lt;/strong&gt; Students are taught to understand childbirth and the importance of Thai midwifery and the Thai culture of postpartum lying-in by fire. They also study the anatomy of men and women of child-bearing age, conception, pregnancy and the process of assisting childbirth in normal labor.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;strong&gt;2.&lt;span class=&quot;Apple-tab-span&quot; style=&quot;white-space:pre&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;Thai Midwifery&lt;/strong&gt; Students learn the Mother and Child Scripture which covers normal and abnormal symptoms during pregnancy. At the end of their studies, students should be able to connect Thai midwifery theory and modern midwifery.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Thai midwifery students also have to undertake internships at community hospitals so that they can practice the whole process, beginning with prenatal health care. Students have to be able to perform obstetrical examinations, evaluate the age of the foetus and determine the delivery date. During childbirth assistance, students have to examine or treat patients by means of Thai traditional medicine. On the point of delivery, students also have to assist pregnant women in normal labor and care for their infants. They should also be able to provide post-partum treatment if any abnormality occurs or provide post-partum care, such as applying compresses to the breast in case milk is scarce or mothers cannot breastfeed, or giving basic post-partum leg and back massage. Students should be able to explain the principles and benefits of Thai postpartum lying-in by fire which includes massage, herbal compresses, sitting above charcoal, herbal saunas, herbal bathing, heated salt-filled pot compresses and abdominal wrapping. They should also be able to correctly and appropriately advise mothers on postpartum self-care.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; Thai massage is part of the national wisdom of the Thai people and has been passed on and accepted from the past to the present. Thai massage can be employed as a treatment and it is regarded as being beneficial for both health and beauty. Compression and touching can increase blood circulation, resulting in muscle relaxation, the loosening of stiffness and the refreshing and relaxation of the mind.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;', 'nopic.png', '2010-06-28'),
(12, 'Teacher', '', 'nopic.png', '2010-06-28'),
(13, 'Traditional Thai Medicine Hospital', '&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;images/photo1.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; height: 200px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; The Traditional Thai Medicine Hospital, Prince of Songkla University, was mainly founded to offer traditional Thai medicine profession for examination and treatment services to the public. The hospital also provides training courses to traditional Thai medicine students&amp;nbsp;during their period of internship so that before earning the degree of Bachelor of Thai Traditional Medicine, they gain both professional practice and experience in the field. They learn to admit patients, inquire about patients and keep their profiles; carry out physical examinations, diagnoses, provide treatment and offer rehabilitation programs according to the theory and principles of Thai traditional medicine. These include prescribing medicine, advising on medicine usage, medicine preparation and prescription, giving therapy in the form of Thai massage, heating, applying compresses and hermit exercise, following-up courses of treatment and the management of Thai traditional medicine hospitals according to related laws and regulations. These skills will equip students of traditional Thai medicine with the knowledge, professional skills, leadership skills and ethics which are deemed to be the desirable qualities of personnel engaged in the practice of Thai traditional medicine.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Mission&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;ol&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		To offer standardized professional services in Thai traditional medicine which are accepted in the Asian region, and to act as a role model for Thai traditional medical professionals.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		To give professional services in Thai traditional medicine to the general public which emphasize the development of standardized services.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		To be an institution for internship in Thai traditional medicine, Thai traditional pharmacy, Thai massage and Thai midwifery.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ol&gt;\r\n', 'hosttm.jpg', '2010-06-28'),
(14, 'Introduction video', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Introduction video The Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;object height=&quot;344&quot; width=&quot;425&quot;&gt;&lt;param name=&quot;movie&quot; value=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/v/rp0k-FF48b8&amp;amp;hl=en&amp;amp;fs=1&quot; /&gt;&lt;param name=&quot;allowFullScreen&quot; value=&quot;true&quot; /&gt;&lt;param name=&quot;allowscriptaccess&quot; value=&quot;always&quot; /&gt;&lt;embed allowfullscreen=&quot;true&quot; allowscriptaccess=&quot;always&quot; height=&quot;344&quot; src=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/v/rp0k-FF48b8&amp;amp;hl=en&amp;amp;fs=1&quot; type=&quot;application/x-shockwave-flash&quot; width=&quot;425&quot;&gt;&lt;/embed&gt;&lt;/object&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;History of&amp;nbsp;Traditional Thai Medicine&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;object height=&quot;385&quot; width=&quot;480&quot;&gt;&lt;param name=&quot;movie&quot; value=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/v/hEpTja7zq28&amp;amp;hl=en_US&amp;amp;fs=1&amp;amp;rel=0&quot; /&gt;&lt;param name=&quot;allowFullScreen&quot; value=&quot;true&quot; /&gt;&lt;param name=&quot;allowscriptaccess&quot; value=&quot;always&quot; /&gt;&lt;embed allowfullscreen=&quot;true&quot; allowscriptaccess=&quot;always&quot; height=&quot;385&quot; src=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/v/hEpTja7zq28&amp;amp;hl=en_US&amp;amp;fs=1&amp;amp;rel=0&quot; type=&quot;application/x-shockwave-flash&quot; width=&quot;480&quot;&gt;&lt;/embed&gt;&lt;/object&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'vdo.jpg', '2010-06-28'),
(15, ' University of  Novi Sad, Serbia', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	On February 15, 2010 &amp;nbsp;Associate Professor Sanan Subhadhirasakul, Dean of the Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine and TTM staff &amp;nbsp;welcomed four distinguished delegates from the University of &amp;nbsp; Novi Sad, Serbia. These were: Professor Dr. Srdjan Kolakovic, leader of UNS Delegation, &amp;nbsp;Professor Dr. Nikola Grujic, Dean of the Faculty of Medicine, &amp;nbsp;Professor Dr. Jovan Popovic, Vice Dean of the Faculty of Medicine and Professor Dr. Goran Marusic, Vice Dean of the Faculty of Medicine.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;uploads/new1-01.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; height: 200px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	The visitors visited the Faculty of traditional Thai Medicine and &amp;nbsp;discussed TTM research. They then proceeded to the Traditional Thai Medicine Hospital and had a foot massage, an experience which was new and impressive for them.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;uploads/new1-02.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; height: 200px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'novisad.jpg', '2010-06-28'),
(16, 'Royal University of Bhutan', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	The Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine received a visit from seven distinguished delegates from the Royal University of Bhutan, on June 1, 2010. The visitors led by Dasho Pema Thinley, Vice Chancellor, Royal University of Bhutan, aim to visit universities, research institutes and organizations, study and training centers dealing with academic programs, research and training in the area of rural development, entrepreneurship programs, traditional medicines, engineering. Through meeting and interactions with relevant officials, university staff and other professionals, the expectation of the study-visit is to establish an understanding with the relevant institutions for networking and collaboration.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;uploads/new2-01.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; height: 200px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	Associate Professor Dr. Sanan Subhateerasakul, Dean of the Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine welcomed them to the Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine and Traditional Thai Medicine Hospital. Our visitors were keen to learn more about TTM and they discussed the details of Traditional Medicine with representatives from our staff during the welcoming meeting. They also visited the faculties of Agro-industry and PSU-Business Incubation Center.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;uploads/new2-02.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; height: 200px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'new2010.JPG', '2010-06-28'),
(17, 'Tub-Mhor-Gleu', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	By&amp;hellip;Miss Sirinthip Vitchayavoranan&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;Tub-Mhor-Gleu&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt; or heated salt-filled pot is a postpartum health care method to help the uterus fit in its right position. The heat from the pot helps to burn down fat and flatten the stomach. This traditional practice also relieves muscular pain and aches, help improve blood circulation and clear up lochia more smoothly and thoroughly leading to the drying up of the uterus. A postpartum mother experiencing normal labor should receive the treatment 10 days after giving birth to a baby, whereas a mother experiencing a cesarean section would need at least a month before receiving the treatment. Normally a mother is given &amp;ldquo;Tub-Mhor-Gleu&amp;rdquo; treatment once a day for a minimum of 1 week to the maximum of 2 months. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;uploads/a1-01.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; height: 200px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;&amp;ldquo;Tub-Mhor-Gleu&amp;rdquo; Component&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;ol&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		2 small clay pots&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		1 piece of 50 x 50 cm. unbleached natural cotton&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		a charcoal or electric stove&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		rough-grained salt (an amount sufficient to fill up the pot)&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		50 g &amp;nbsp;of Zingiber cassumunar&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		50 g of Curcuma amada&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		2 Crinum Lily leaves&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		1.5 g of Borneol&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		1.5 g of Camphor&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ol&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;uploads/a1-02.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 600px; height: 200px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;&amp;ldquo;Tub-Mhor-Gleu&amp;rdquo; Treatment Procedure&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ol&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Prepare 2 salt-filled pots. Heat the pots until hearing cracklings of salt grains.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Wrap each heated salt-filled pot with unbleached natural cloth which is layered with 5 medicinal herbs.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Have the postpartum mother lie on the stomach. &amp;nbsp;Put the heated salt-filled pot on her hips, bottom, legs, waist and back, respectively. &amp;nbsp;Apply some weight on the pot.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Have the postpartum mother lie on the back. Put the heated salt-filled pot on her upper legs. &amp;nbsp;Apply some weight on the pot.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		When the &amp;ldquo;Mhor-Gleu&amp;rdquo; or salt-filled pot becomes slightly cooler, put it on the mother&amp;rsquo;s stomach. Apply weight firmly on the uterus for 30 seconds; repeat this step for at least 10 minutes.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ol&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;em&gt;Notes:&lt;/em&gt; Step 3, 4, and 5 takes approximate 30 minutes each. Use the two pots alternately.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Do&amp;rsquo;s and Don&amp;rsquo;t&amp;rsquo;s in Giving &amp;ldquo;Tub-Mhor-Gleu&amp;rdquo; Treatment&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Do&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;ol&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Have the postpartum mother urinate before receiving the &amp;ldquo;Tub-Mhor-Gleu&amp;rdquo; &amp;nbsp; treatment.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Remove the gas in the patient&amp;rsquo;s stomach before giving &amp;ldquo;Tub-Mhor-Gleu&amp;rdquo; treatment to prevent intestine dilatation.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Take special care when apply the treatment on epigastrium, costa border, pelvis bone, hip bone, pubic symphysis, spine etc. (Apply significant less weight because the treatment may cause bruises or damages.)&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ol&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Don&amp;rsquo;t&amp;rsquo;s&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ol&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Don&amp;rsquo;t apply &amp;ldquo;Tub-Mhor-Gleu&amp;rdquo; treatment to a pregnant woman.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Don&amp;rsquo;t apply &amp;ldquo;Tub-Mhor-Gleu&amp;rdquo; treatment in case of severe stomachache, fever, pain or inflammation of any organ.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Don&amp;rsquo;t apply &amp;ldquo;Tub-Mhor-Gleu&amp;rdquo; treatment after eating.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Don&amp;rsquo;t let the postpartum mother sit up or stand up right after receiving &amp;ldquo;Tub-Mhor-Gleu&amp;rdquo; &amp;nbsp; treatment to prevent getting faint.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ol&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Reference&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	กัญจนี พลอินทร์ และคณะ. (2550). เอกสารประกอบคำสอนรายวิชาผดุงครรภ์แผนไทย (170-304)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	คณะการแพทย์แผนไทย &amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;Apple-tab-span&quot; style=&quot;white-space:pre&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;มหาวิทยาลัยสงขลานครินทร์; 208-209.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', 'tum.jpg', '2010-06-28'),
(18, 'The Four Elements (tard) of the Body', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	By &amp;nbsp;Pichamon Akarayosapong&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;According to Traditional Thai Medicine (TTM), the human body is composed of four elements (or &amp;lsquo;tard&amp;rsquo; in the Thai language), i.e., earth, water, wind and fire. The balance of the four elements leads to a person&amp;rsquo;s good health. In contrast, if an imbalance of these elements occurs, e.g. under-function, over-function and malfunction in any of the four elements, a person will fall ill. In addition to such imbalance of the 4 internal elements, illness may result if the four internal elements do not correspond with the external element, i.e. environment.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/attachment/1278298121_6052db69.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 250px; height: 257px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;h4&gt;\r\n	&amp;ldquo;Tard-chao-ruan&amp;rdquo; or the dominant element of the body&amp;nbsp;&lt;/h4&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;As stated above, an individual has one dominant element called &amp;ldquo;Tard-chao-ruan&amp;rdquo;, which is determined by the date and month of his/her conception. The dominant element plays an important role in determining the person&amp;rsquo;s characteristics. appearance and their susceptibility to certain ailments. Therefore, it is recommended in TTM that each individual has a diets of particular flavors, as described below :&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/attachment/1278298121_6436324b.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 83px; height: 164px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Fire (People born in Jan.-March)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;These people usually have thin bodies, fairly dark skin with freckles, wrinkle skin, soft hair &amp;amp; facial hair, gray hair at young age, loose muscles and joints, bad breath and body odor. and moderate sexual desire.&amp;nbsp;They tend to be bald, impatient, short-tempered and have good metabolisms leading to their being frequent eater of large portions.&amp;nbsp;Their appropriate diets include cool, bitter flavored or bland food such as water melon, cucumber (cool); Siamese cassia, gourd (bitter), radish, eggplant, cabbage (tasteless), etc.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/attachment/1278298121_147210d6.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 68px; height: 178px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Wind (People born in April.-June)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; These people usually have tall and thin bodies, dry skin, sleeping problem, low voice, unclear speech and low sexual desire. Their joints crackle when they make any movement. They are envious, timid, &amp;nbsp;talkative and always intolerate to cold. Their &amp;nbsp;diet should include spicy flavored food such as ginger, galangal, &amp;nbsp;lemongrass, pepper, chili pepper, basil, holy basil, fennel, garlic, etc.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/attachment/1278298121_6182a03e.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 83px; height: 171px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Water (People born in July-Sep.)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;These people usually have nice bodies, healthy skin, beautiful eyes, thick hair, clear voice, steady stride walk and good sexual desire. They are slow eater, slow worker as well as tolerant to heat, cold and hunger.Their ideal diet include sour and bitter flavored food, such as orange tomato, pineapple, kaffir lime, lime, young tamarind leaf (sour);Chinese bitter cucumber-chinese, bitter gourd (bitter), etc.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/attachment/1278298121_11737042.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 84px; height: 156px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Earth &amp;nbsp;(People born in Oct.-Dec.)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;These people usually have tall and large bodies, fairly dark complexion, thick hair, loud voice, strong bones and joints and healthy organs.Their appropriate diets include astringent, sweet or salty flavored food and starchy vegetables such as guava (astringent); rambutan, mangosteen, banana (sweet); salt (salty); taro root, yam, potato (starchy vegetables), etc.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', 'element.jpg', '2010-07-05'),
(21, 'Miracles of Honey', '&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/english/uploads/Honey.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 236px; height: 211px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Honey is a sweetener in several diets as well as a medicine. The essential components in honey are: water around 20 percent, many types of sugar, namely, glucose, and fructose around 79 percent and mixed components &amp;ndash; acid, vitamin, enzyme, and mineral around 0.5 percent. The major constituent is sugar which is single molecule sugar and this can easily be absorbed into the body.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; Honey has many medicinal properties. Honey is a promoter of normal physiological functions and can ensure a sound sleep and a good level of energy. Honey has laxative properties as well as soothing properties. It can heal internal wounds and it is therefore indicated for cases of peptic and duodenal ulcers. &amp;nbsp;It is also useful in the healing of external wounds and can be applied on the skin to alleviate inflammation. Even though honey is sweet, it does not cause tooth decay or any other problems which are normally caused by refined sugar. In Traditional Thai medicine, honey is used to flavor some medicine.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;In general Traditional Thai medicine principle, honey is contraindicated to patients who have jaundice &amp;ndash; yellow body and conjunctiva, patients who have a lot of sputum and complication with pulmonary disease, or patients who have problem with lymphoid tissue &amp;ndash; abscess. The most important contraindication is in patients with diabetes mellitus because honey is comprised of glucose and fructose that can be absorbed immediately until sugar level goes very high.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;The time which is appropriate for taking honey is about half hour before meals. Honey can be taken with warm water (not &amp;nbsp;over 40 C). It can inhibit acids released from gastric juices. Thus &amp;nbsp;honey can reduce gastric irritation in patients with peptic ulcer. Taking honey with cool water should be done after meals &amp;nbsp;because taking it immediately can contribute to high sugar level leading to harder function of pancreas. Moreover, it increases enzyme level in the digestive system.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;div&gt;\r\n		Written by&lt;/div&gt;\r\n	&lt;div&gt;\r\n		Mr. Chayanon Chaowuttikul &amp;nbsp;5011410007&lt;/div&gt;\r\n	&lt;div&gt;\r\n		Miss Juthamas Korkitpisarn 5011410047&lt;/div&gt;\r\n	&lt;div&gt;\r\n		&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n	&lt;div&gt;\r\n		&lt;pre&gt;\r\n		Advicer : Ms.Stefania Vignotto\r\n&lt;/pre&gt;\r\n		&lt;pre&gt;\r\n		Course co-ordinator : JATSADAPORN  BOONPHOMEE\r\n                              NANTIYA  JOYCHARAT (Ph.D.)\r\n\r\n&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/read.php?39&quot;&gt;Thai version&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;\r\n	&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;/div&gt;', 'honey.jpg', '2010-08-27'),
(20, 'The Cardioprotective Potential of Punica Granatum', '&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/attachment/1282708466_94315335.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 200px; height: 192px; &quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; Punica granatum originated in Persia or what is now the Iranian Plateau. The fruit of Punica granatum is commonly known as pomegranate. It is edible, with a sweet and sour taste. The juice of pomegranate contains Vitamin C and other minerals which are beneficial to the body. The juice makes a refreshing drink.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; The ancient Persian medical formulations indicated that pomegranate has many benefits such as helping to regulate the function of the urinary system. It assists the work of the heart and liver; it purifies the blood, it helps digestion and removes excess fat, it adjusts the hormonal balance in postmenopausal women and fights impotence; it prevents forgetfulness and skin conditions.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Latest research has helped confirming the medicinal properties of pomegranate.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; The peel of pomegranate contains high tannin which is used to cure dysentery, kill many types of bacteria and reduce inflammation. In addition, it was found that pomegranate has an inhibitory effect upon the propagation of cancer cells and thus helps fight many types of cancer growths such as colon cancer, esophagus cancer, liver cancer, breast cancer, prostate cancer etc.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Medical Research in the United States has found that Punica contains many antioxidants and is highly efficient in reducing lipid accumulation in the arterial walls, clotting and blood vessel blockages.&amp;nbsp;These conditions normally lead to subsequent ischemic heart disease. Pomegranate reduces the thickness of the blood and thus it acts as a &amp;ldquo;blood conditioner&amp;rdquo;. In addition, compounds from pomegranate nourish the liver. They prevent toxic effects and inhibit liver cancer cells as well.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; Pharmacological studies found that the root bark of pomegranate showed anti-bacterial activity and can treat intestinal parasites, mainly tapeworm. In addition, it has shown an anti-typhoid potential as well as an anti-fungal action on the skin. Thai Traditional Medicine uses the properties of Punica in different ways.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;The acerbity of the leaves is used to treat diarrhea and heal wounds. Flowers are used to treat ear inflammation. The pulp is a mild laxative and a tonic to the heart.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;The peel is also used for treating diarrhea, check any pathological discharge and as a disinfectant.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;The boiled root bark is used to treat leucorrhea, pathological bleeding and to excrete worms. In addition, in Chinese traditional medicine, pomegranate is considered &amp;ldquo;cool sweet sour&amp;rdquo; and it helps to quench the thirst and prevent anemia, treat bad breath, fever, conjunctivitis, bronchitis and is a tonic to the eyes.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	By &amp;nbsp; Miss. Salaya Kuning No.5011410010&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Miss. Sirirut tongrod No.5011410053&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;pre&gt;\r\n	Advicer : Ms.Stefania Vignotto\r\n&lt;/pre&gt;\r\n	&lt;pre&gt;\r\n	Course co-ordinator : JATSADAPORN  BOONPHOMEE\r\n                                NANTIYA  JOYCHARAT (Ph.D.)&lt;/pre&gt;\r\n&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	Reference: http://www.vcharkarn.com&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/read.php?39&quot;&gt;Read Thai Version&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'believe_97.jpg', '2010-08-25');
