(24, 'Delegation from KMU visits Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine', '&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/english/images/image154.jpeg&quot; style=&quot;width: 300px; height: 225px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; Delegation from Kunming Medical University, P.R. China visited the faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine on 19 January 2010. Dr.Sasitorn &amp;nbsp;Chusri, Assistant Dean for Research and International Affairs and administrators offered a warm welcome to our visitors. The meeting gave everyone the opportunity to exchange information about Chinese and Thai traditional medicine.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/english/images/image254.jpeg&quot; style=&quot;width: 250px; height: 188px; &quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/english/images/image354.jpeg&quot; style=&quot;width: 250px; height: 188px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;The delegation also visited our Traditional Thai Medicine hospital. Executives were offered Thai massage. Students had a chance to make a hot herbal compressed ball which was certainly fun for them. &amp;nbsp;The purpose of the visit, under the MOU between PSU and KMA, were to study the curriculum, teaching technique, and research methods.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'news154.jpg', '2011-03-15'),
(22, 'Royal Highness Princess Maha Chakri Sirindhorn Brings the International Award Committee of the Prince Mahidol Foundation to PSU', '&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;uploads/phoca_thumb_l_021053-055.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 300px; height: 225px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Her Royal Highness Princess Maha Chakri Sirindhorn granted Prince of Songkla University the opportunity to receive Her Royal Highness and distinguished guests from the International Award Committee of the Prince Mahidol Foundation from October 2-3, 2010.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;The object of Her Royal Highness visit was to open the ceremony of the Southern Medical Rehabilitation Centre on October 3, 2010 at Songklanagarind Hospital. Moreover, on the evening of October 2, 2010, The Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine had the opportunity to join the reception dinner. For the Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine&amp;rsquo;s booth, we presented &amp;ldquo;Germinated Brown Rice Drink and Germinated Brown Rive Ice cream&amp;rdquo;. During the reception, Her Royal Highness played music with the PSU band. This pleased all participants very much.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;uploads/phoca_thumb_l_021053-049.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 262px; height: 347px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;On October 3, 2010, Her Royal Highness and the visitors visited various exhibitions from several faculties at the PSU International Convention Centre. The Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine showed research work, herbal products and Thai medicine system of diagnosis and cure. Visitors were particularly interested in Thai massage.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Our representatives were very delighted to have a chance to see Her Royal Highness closely.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', 'phoca_thumb_l_021053-055.jpg', '2010-12-13'),
(23, 'Her Excellency Sirpa Maenpaa , The Ambassador of The Republic of Finland visited The Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine', '&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;uploads/IMG_0018.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 364px; height: 273px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	The Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine at PSU had the honor of welcoming H.E Sirpa Maenpaa, The Ambassador of The Republic of Finland to PSU, on October 11, 2010. Her Excellency was warmly welcomed by PSU representatives, led by Associate Professor &amp;nbsp;Dr.Chatchai Ratanachai, Vice President for Outreach and International Affairs; Associate Professor Dr.Sanan &amp;nbsp;Subhadhirasakul, Dean of the Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine and Dr.Sasitorn &amp;nbsp;Chusri, Assistant Dean for Research and International Affairs.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	Our representative introduced history of Traditional Thai Medicine and of the faculty via DVD presentations. Moreover, Her Excellency paid a visit to the Traditional Thai Medicine Hospital. We offered a Thai massage, an experience which left a positive impression on Her Excellency.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	At the end, Associate Professor Dr. Sanan offered some souvenirs to Her Excellency.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n', 'IMG_0018.jpg', '2010-12-13'),
(26, 'Scholarship', '&lt;h2&gt;\r\n	Bachelor&amp;#39;s Degree&lt;/h2&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;Offer of scholarship to South East Asia Students&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	The Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine, Prince of Songkla University (PSU), Thailand, invites nationals of South East Asia to apply for academic year 2012. The scholarship will be granted to students to study in Thailand in the undergraduate program.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	The scholarship will be granted to the applicants who meet acceptance criteria outlined below. The scholarship will include tuition fees, living allowances, and accommodation.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;ELIGIBILITY&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	Eligible applicants must satisfy the following criteria:&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Hold a High School Certificate or a qualification equivalent to Grade 12 Certificate&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Proficiency in Thai and English&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Maximum age: 25 years (calculated up to October 1st, 2012)&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Be of good health physically and mentally&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;DURATION OF SCHOLARSHIPS&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	Four academic years (2012&amp;ndash; 2015)&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	** The PSU academic year has two semesters: June to October and November to March.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;SCHOLARSHIP BENEFITS&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Monthly living allowance: US$ 234 (7,000 Baht)&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Monthly housing allowance: US$ 100 (3,000 Baht)&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Visa fees: US$ 97 (2,900 Baht) per academic year&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Health Insurance: US$ 10 (300 Baht) per academic year&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Miscellaneous expenses according to the field of study: US$ 134&amp;nbsp; (4,000 Baht) per academic year.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	** The scholarship students must be responsible for their own travel expenses from their home to PSU.&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;DOCUMENTS REQUIRED FOR APPLICATION&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		Original copy of the Application Form with passport sized photographs taken not more than six months from the deadline of application.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		A certified copy of high school certificate&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;\r\n		A certified copy of transcript of records for high school study with grades&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; and grade point average in English&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&lt;strong&gt;WHERE TO SUBMIT APPLICATION FORM&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	The applicants are recommended to submit the application form and all required documents electronically (via e-mail) to: &lt;strong&gt;sasitorn.chu@psu.ac.th&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;rattanavilai.th@psu.ac.th&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '150px-Scholarship.jpg', '2011-05-02'),
(27, 'From the Bottom of Hearts', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Every civilizations, has a medical history differently. In Thailand, there was &amp;nbsp;the important medical history called Traditional Thai Medicine. &amp;mdash; it&amp;#39;s about combining several knowledge about treatment of diseases and health care including Using Herbs, Throat painting, Massage, Massage with a compress, Tattooing (Red and black tattoo similar to Chinese acupuncture or Chinese reflexology) and lying near the fire after childbirth etc. which depend on their belief, culture and depend on individual method. In the reign of King Narai The Great, there were missionaries came to Thailand to propagate their religion and also brought the knowledge of Ancient Western Medicine came to use in Thailand and had become an Alternative Medicine for Thai people in those time until the Rattanakosin period, especially reigns of King Rama IV and V, the Orthodox or Conventional Medicine had influenced to Thailand almost completely. In addition, it has been studied widely, every experiment were confirmed by science method and those experimental results were reliable. We could understand them concretely and we couldn&amp;rsquo;t argue them. So Orthodox Medicine or Conventional Medicine has become to a Principal Medicine of Thailand implicitly. Although Siriraj Hospital was built for medical care for patients by Traditional Thai Medicine in 1888 according to His Majesty King Chulalongkorn Ordered but the Rockefeller Foundation has an influence to Thai people and began to use Health Professionals Act then Traditional Thai Medicine was stopped the role since then (1). &amp;nbsp;Orthodox Medicine prefer separating parts of &amp;nbsp;human body and there were specialists who were highly trained in specific branches. Also, there were developed technologies and medical devices a lot. Western Medicine has been studied widely&amp;mdash;it is recognized that Western Medicine was more effective and efficient than Traditional Thai Medicine. In the other hand, it cause using of medicine and medical tool too extravagant and governments might lose money more than is necessary. In addition, medicine might cause side effects to human body and developed medical technologies such as radiation or chemotherapy helping reduced cancer cell size might cause side effects to human body too. Patients not only lose money but they liked to rely on Doctor only and unknown to care their health by themselves.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In past, we used Traditional Thai Medicine to treat our health and we didn&amp;rsquo;t need to see a doctor to cure some symptoms that we could treat those symptoms by ourselves but the most important problems are people in present believed that Thai Traditional Medicine has non-standard theory, has unbelievable research evidences and must use long time to treat. So Traditional Thai Medicine is not popular enough in present (2). However the direction of health care in this century give the important to Holistic health care more than Fragmented-form health care. Therefore returning to Traditional Thai Medicine is an interesting alternative to care your health by yourself. Above all else, the government and private agencies should work together to develop Traditional Thai Medicine.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'teacher.jpg', '2011-11-01'),
(28, ' Rarngjeud', '&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.ttmed.psu.ac.th/attachment/1320132032_464734f4.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 635px; height: 154px; &quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; The experience with agriculturist in the community found &amp;nbsp;they has using chemicals &amp;nbsp;in the agricultural such as &amp;nbsp;insecticide , herbicide or chemical fertilizer. Cause they exposed to chemicals regularly. In addition the mostly of &amp;nbsp;agriculturists &amp;nbsp;don&amp;rsquo;t &amp;nbsp;protect &amp;nbsp;themselves &amp;nbsp;from chemicals for example &amp;nbsp;do not wash their hands after working, have a meal at work. So, agriculturist &amp;nbsp;have been chemical &amp;nbsp;more than consumers and chemicals that have accumulated in their bodies that may be causing harm in the future. One option to Thai farmers to reduce the accumulation of toxins in the body using herbs &amp;ldquo;Rarngjeud&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Rarngjeud &amp;nbsp;easily &amp;nbsp;found in rural areas and made a tea to drink instead of water. &amp;nbsp;To destroy and &amp;nbsp;excreted chemical residues in the body. The toxicity of pesticides can cause dizziness, nausea, vomiting, angina, and Dyspnoea. This herb can to excrete those harmful chemicals out.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &lt;em&gt;Thunbergia laurifolia&lt;/em&gt; Linn. is known in Thai as &amp;ldquo;Rarngjeud&amp;rdquo;. It a member of the Acanthus family. It is a climbing vine with other tree. &lt;em&gt;T laurifolia&lt;/em&gt;. &amp;nbsp;is a &amp;nbsp;Thai herb that has scientifically confirmed that Efficacy treatment of Diarrhea, Eczema, Toxic of pesticide in animal, Toxin of pesticide, Chemical toxic, alcoholism, etc. Currently, there are products made from Rarng Jeud &amp;nbsp;like tea and beverage products.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;In addition , Consumer said this herb can to cure the many poison such as the dog was poisoned and can help to survive it becase the owner take of juice from Thunbergia laurifolia L. &amp;nbsp;In the past, who have been poisoned. They usually solve with Thunbergia laurifolia L. same . Research studies have reported can reduce fever in rats were found Thunbergia laurifolia L. to be well-tested &amp;nbsp;to solve a toxic of Folidol-E pesticide.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; Found that water extracted from the leaves with Nropine can reduce the mortality of animals experiment in mice and anti-toxin from pesticides are rganophosphate which research data is the information of use for Thai traditional medicine.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;So, Rarngjeud is health care alternative &amp;nbsp;for farmer because it excrete or reduce the toxin in your body but it not prevent the toxins into the body.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'rajan11.jpeg', '2011-11-01'),
(29, 'The First Natural Product Meeting, 2011', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	On October 17-18, 2011, the first Natural Product Meeting of 2011 was held at Khaolak Emerald Beach Resort &amp;amp; Spa, Phang Nga, Thailand. Our bachelor and master&amp;rsquo;s degree students presented at the conference sharing their knowledge of natural medicines and products. &amp;nbsp; In addition, the faculty of traditional Thai Medicine was invited to attend the conference by the Natural Product Research Center&amp;rsquo;s Faculty of Science. &amp;nbsp;This opportunity allowed our group to set up a booth offering Thai traditional medicines and Thai massages to both Thais and foreigners. The faculty had four staff members, three traditional Thai Medicine doctors, and an international affairs officer at the booth.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	While participating in the conference, our staff exchanged ideas with Thais and foreign students. We presented the values of using Thai herbs and of having Thai massages. &amp;nbsp;This was done while academic research in support of Thai Medicine was presented. We provided Thai medicines, diagnosed maladies by hand, and Thai massages. The Thai Medicine booth attracted many of the participants; a large majority of them were foreigners from Malaysia, India, Indonesia, and other Asian countries. &amp;nbsp;All senior year and master&amp;rsquo;s students found the visit a valuable experience from listening to presentations and presenting their knowledge and goals to the participants. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	Believing that Thai Medicine is an important aspect of curing maladies, this opportunity strengthened our personal beliefs, allowed us to learn from others, and gave us the experience to support our products and treatments while sharing with the participants. &amp;nbsp;It was a much-appreciated experience.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;embed type=&quot;application/x-shockwave-flash&quot; src=&quot;https://picasaweb.google.com/s/c/bin/slideshow.swf&quot; width=&quot;400&quot; height=&quot;267&quot; flashvars=&quot;host=picasaweb.google.com&amp;hl=th&amp;feat=flashalbum&amp;RGB=0x000000&amp;feed=https%3A%2F%2Fpicasaweb.google.com%2Fdata%2Ffeed%2Fapi%2Fuser%2Fttmed.psu%2Falbumid%2F5680637231436415857%3Falt%3Drss%26kind%3Dphoto%26hl%3Dth&quot; pluginspage=&quot;http://www.macromedia.com/go/getflashplayer&quot;&gt;&lt;/embed&gt;', '6.jpg', '2011-11-30'),
(30, 'Visitors from Yunnan Provincial Hospital of Traditional Chinese Medicine', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;The faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine received a visit of 15 staff members from Yunnan Provincial Hospital of Traditional Chinese Medicine accompanied by Assoc. Prof. Wimonrat Chongcharean from faculty of Nursing on December 2, 2011. The objectives of their visit were to learn more about the education system, research, and academic services of TTM and to discuss possible future cooperation.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;They were warmly received by Dr.Oratai Neamsuvan, Associate Dean for Quality Assurance and Planning Affairs, Dr.Sasitorn Chusri, Assistant Dean for Research and International Affairs, Mr.Mana Rakwong, Assistant Dean for Students and Academic Services Affairs, and Miss Rattanavilai Thawornsuwon, an International Affair officer at Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;During the conference, all participants had the opportunity to listen to discussions of the educational system in TTM and to ask questions. The representatives expressed their hope for a fruitful collaboration between TTM and Traditional Chinese Medicine.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&lt;embed flashvars=&quot;host=picasaweb.google.com&amp;amp;hl=th&amp;amp;feat=flashalbum&amp;amp;RGB=0x000000&amp;amp;feed=https%3A%2F%2Fpicasaweb.google.com%2Fdata%2Ffeed%2Fapi%2Fuser%2Fttmed.psu%2Falbumid%2F5685903011141582385%3Falt%3Drss%26kind%3Dphoto%26hl%3Dth&quot; height=&quot;267&quot; pluginspage=&quot;http://www.macromedia.com/go/getflashplayer&quot; src=&quot;https://picasaweb.google.com/s/c/bin/slideshow.swf&quot; type=&quot;application/x-shockwave-flash&quot; width=&quot;400&quot;&gt;&lt;/embed&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'IMG_0014.JPG', '2011-12-14'),
(31, 'Visitors from Tinan Bian China Travel Union Company Limited', '&lt;p&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	On March 06, 2012, Dr.Sasitorn Chusri, Assistant Dean for Research and International Affairs and Miss Rattanavilai Thawornsuwon, an International Affair officer at Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine, gave a warm welcome to 2 representatives from China Travel Union Company Limited from China, namely Ms. Bian Ruo Zhi, Chairman, together with Ms.Cao Sha, Manager. Also 3 delegates from PSU joined this meeting, &amp;nbsp;Dr. Ram Yamsaengsung, Assistant President for Research and Graduate Studies, &amp;nbsp;Mr. Vorasan Sobhon, Assistant Dean of Graduate school along with An International Affair Officer of Graduate School.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	The object of their visit was to receive more information about our graduate program. Therefore, they would have detailed information to give to Chinese students who desire to study at TTM&amp;rsquo;s faculty. Our guests shared their ideas and wishes about the program such as having a short massage training program.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	After our discussion, the Traditional Thai Medicine Hospital offered our guests a Thai massage which made a favorable impression upon them.&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: center; &quot;&gt;\r\n	&lt;embed flashvars=&quot;host=picasaweb.google.com&amp;amp;hl=th&amp;amp;feat=flashalbum&amp;amp;RGB=0x000000&amp;amp;feed=https%3A%2F%2Fpicasaweb.google.com%2Fdata%2Ffeed%2Fapi%2Fuser%2F117052859763469616076%2Falbumid%2F5722553366093807281%3Falt%3Drss%26kind%3Dphoto%26hl%3Dth&quot; height=&quot;192&quot; pluginspage=&quot;http://www.macromedia.com/go/getflashplayer&quot; src=&quot;https://picasaweb.google.com/s/c/bin/slideshow.swf&quot; type=&quot;application/x-shockwave-flash&quot; width=&quot;288&quot;&gt;&lt;/embed&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'chain55.GIF', '2012-03-22'),
(32, 'Lecturers and Students from JXNU visit TTM', '<p>\r\n	 TTM received a group of visitors from Jiangxi Normal University (JXNU), P.R. China in January 29, 2013. Two lecturers and ten students visited TTM for half day under the staff and students exchange program between our universities. Our 12 Chinese guests were warmly welcomed at the faculty by Miss Rattanavilai Thawornsuwon, International Affair Officer of Traditional Thai Medicine. They spent time to gain experiences in making Somporn&rsquo;s Thai herb salad which healthy ingredients. Two Thai Traditional Medicine doctors: Mr. Somchai Aonthong and Miss Pirunrat Sae-lim taught them how to make it. They enjoyed participating in our activities. After that, they also had a chance to visit our Traditional Thai Medicine Hospital.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\"> </span>It was a great opportunity to widen the learning environment for the students and offer them the opportunity to learn about another culture and academic atmosphere.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"uploads/chain.jpg\" /></p>', 'IMG_0156.JPG', '2013-02-08'),
(33, 'Visitors from Jiangxi University of Science and Technology (JUST)', '<p>\r\n  <img src=\"uploads/china8-56.JPG\" />\r\n</p>\r\n<p>On August 8, 2013, the PSU Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine, Miss Rattanavilai Thawornsuwon , an International Affair Officer and Miss Supannika Jaisaman, Traditional Thai Medicine Doctor, expressed their warmth and hospitality to a group of students and staff  from Jiangxi University of Science and Technology (JUST), P.R. China,  who paid a visit to PSU during their study trip under the MOU between our universities. The Chinese guests experienced making Thai herbal scrub. During their workshop, it was very nice to have junior and senior Traditional Thai Medicine students participating in the activity. Our guests were excited to make their own Thai herbal scrub. Also, at the end of the activity, both Thai and Chinese students had a chance to sing the Prince of Songkla University song. It was very nice for Thai students to teach Chinese students sing the University theme song. The students enjoyed very much taking part in the activities. These activities were a great opportunity for both Thai and Chinese’s students to exchange and learn together.</p>', 'china8-56.JPG', '2013-08-15'),
(35, 'Visitors from Kunming Medical University', '<p>Two medical bachelor students from Kunming Medical University, P. R. China, led by Assoc. Prof . Long Rong, Vice Dean of School of Basic Medicine and Ms. Li Juan, Teacher for Student Affairs of School of Basic Medicine, visited the Faculty of Traditional Thai Medicine (FTTM) under the MOU between our universities. Our guests visited FTTM from September 17 – 18, 2013 which came under the Culture Exchange Program. Dr. Sasitorn Chusri, Assistant Dean for Research and International Affairs; Dr. Surasak Limsuwan, Lecturer; and Miss Rattanavilai Thawornsuwon , our International Affairs Officer  welcomed our guests at FTTM.\r\n</p><p>During the two-day visit, all participants enjoyed several classes on Traditional Thai medicine which were offered by our lecturers, scientists and Thai medicine doctors. The classes provided for our guests were on Thai massage; on preparation of Thai medicine plus a workshop on how to make hot herbal compress balls.  Two of the lecturers appreciated the hot herbal steam treatment, in particular. In addition, it was a great opportunity for TTM’s students to help our lecturers undertaking these activities. It was great chance for them to communicate with foreign students.</p>\r\n', '260956.jpg', '2013-09-26');

